A note on data frames (extremely short lesson 5)

  • We have gone over the basic data types and structures in R
  • We’re going to learn a little bit more about working with data frames before we move on to the real data

Adding columns and rows in data frame

  • The columns in a data frame are vectors - a series of things that are all the same type.
  • So, if we want to make a new column, we can start by making a new vector (series of things)
# Read in cats if you haven't already
cats <- read.csv("data/feline-data.csv")

# Create new vector for age of cats
age <- c(2, 3, 5)

# What did cats look like again?
cats
##     coat weight likes_string
## 1 calico    2.1            1
## 2  black    5.0            0
## 3  tabby    3.2            1
# Add this vector as a new column with cbind (not overwriting the variable here)
cbind(cats, age)
##     coat weight likes_string age
## 1 calico    2.1            1   2
## 2  black    5.0            0   3
## 3  tabby    3.2            1   5
# What happens if the number of entries in age doesn't match that in cats?
age <- c(2, 3, 5, 12)
cbind(cats, age)
## Error in data.frame(..., check.names = FALSE): arguments imply differing number of rows: 3, 4

R needs the number of elements in the vector (the new column) to match the number of rows already in the table. View them by:

nrow(cats)
## [1] 3
length(age)
## [1] 4

So let’s add that column to cats - remember, you need to reassign the variable if you want it to “save” rather than just print.

age <- c(2, 3, 5)
cats <- cbind(cats, age)

# Cats now has a new column
cats
##     coat weight likes_string age
## 1 calico    2.1            1   2
## 2  black    5.0            0   3
## 3  tabby    3.2            1   5

Adding a new row

Now, what if we want to add a new row of data? Rows can contain elements of different types, so we need to make a list.

# Create a new row for a new cat
newRow <- list("tortoiseshell", 3.3, TRUE, 9)

# Add this row to the data frame with rbind
cats <- rbind(cats, newRow)
## Warning in `[<-.factor`(`*tmp*`, ri, value = "tortoiseshell"): invalid
## factor level, NA generated

But what happened?!

Remember that factors are categories, so R only allows whatever is originally there. What we have added, tortoiseshell, is ‘nonsense’ - it doesn’t fit into the categories in this column, so becomes NA.

Factors

So to add a cat with a tortoiseshell coat, we add tortoiseshell as a level in the factor: we are specifying a new category.

# What are the levels at the moment
levels(cats$coat)
## [1] "black"  "calico" "tabby"
# Add a new one
levels(cats$coat) <- c(levels(cats$coat), "tortoiseshell")

# Check those levels now
levels(cats$coat)
## [1] "black"         "calico"        "tabby"         "tortoiseshell"
# Try adding the new row again
cats <- rbind(cats, list("tortoiseshell", 3.3, TRUE, 9))

This is okay, but another way we can do this is just change that column from a factor to a character vector - we can add whatever we want.

# What's the structure of the cats data frame?
str(cats)
## 'data.frame':    5 obs. of  4 variables:
##  $ coat        : Factor w/ 4 levels "black","calico",..: 2 1 3 NA 4
##  $ weight      : num  2.1 5 3.2 3.3 3.3
##  $ likes_string: int  1 0 1 1 1
##  $ age         : num  2 3 5 9 9
# Change the coat variable to a character
cats$coat <- as.character(cats$coat)
str(cats)
## 'data.frame':    5 obs. of  4 variables:
##  $ coat        : chr  "calico" "black" "tabby" NA ...
##  $ weight      : num  2.1 5 3.2 3.3 3.3
##  $ likes_string: int  1 0 1 1 1
##  $ age         : num  2 3 5 9 9

If you want to avoid this in the first place, you can use stringsAsFactors = FALSE when you originally read in the file.

# Read in cats again, but with new option
cats.nofactors <- read.csv("data/feline-data.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Check out cats 
str(cats.nofactors)
## 'data.frame':    3 obs. of  3 variables:
##  $ coat        : chr  "calico" "black" "tabby"
##  $ weight      : num  2.1 5 3.2
##  $ likes_string: int  1 0 1
# It's a character, so we should have no trouble adding that row.
cats.nofactors <- rbind(catsnofactors, newRow)
## Error in rbind(catsnofactors, newRow): object 'catsnofactors' not found
# Check cats
cats.nofactors
##     coat weight likes_string
## 1 calico    2.1            1
## 2  black    5.0            0
## 3  tabby    3.2            1

DO CHALLENGE ONE. Show them what the original data frame looks like so it’s clearer how to modify it. Then explain:

Factors are stored as integers (as in, category level 1, 2, 3, etc. rather than the actual labels for the categories). So when we convert a factor to numeric, this gives us those underlying numbers, not the labels. If we want those original numbers, we’d take the factor human.age and convert it first to character vector, then to numeric. This can happen in real life, if you read in some data that is supposed to be all numbers but has a letter in there somewhere - if you don’t set stringsAsFactors = FALSE when you read it in, by default it will make that column a factor. You think it’s all numbers, you convert it to numeric, and suddenly everything is wrong.

Removing rows

Let’s go back to our original cats dataframe, where the solved the problem by converting to a character (for example, if you’ve done a lot to the data since and you don’t want to have to go back to reading it in). We still have that crappo row:

cats
##            coat weight likes_string age
## 1        calico    2.1            1   2
## 2         black    5.0            0   3
## 3         tabby    3.2            1   5
## 4          <NA>    3.3            1   9
## 5 tortoiseshell    3.3            1   9

There are a couple of ways we can get rid of that row. We can remove that specific row:

# Show me the cats dataframe without that row
cats[-4,]
##            coat weight likes_string age
## 1        calico    2.1            1   2
## 2         black    5.0            0   3
## 3         tabby    3.2            1   5
## 5 tortoiseshell    3.3            1   9
# If you wanted to remove multiple rows, you can put them in a vector
cats[c(-4, -5),]
##     coat weight likes_string age
## 1 calico    2.1            1   2
## 2  black    5.0            0   3
## 3  tabby    3.2            1   5

We could also remove all rows with NA values - this is easier if you have a big data frame.

# Show me the cats dataframe with all rows containing NA removed
na.omit(cats)
##            coat weight likes_string age
## 1        calico    2.1            1   2
## 2         black    5.0            0   3
## 3         tabby    3.2            1   5
## 5 tortoiseshell    3.3            1   9
# Let's reassign the output so the cats dataframe is actually changed
cats <- na.omit(cats)

Appending to a data frame

Remembering that in a dataframe, the columns are vectors or factors (all the same type), and the rows are lists (can be a collection of things of different types), we can stick two data frames together with rbind:

# Append the rows of cats to cats
cats <- rbind(cats, cats)
cats
##             coat weight likes_string age
## 1         calico    2.1            1   2
## 2          black    5.0            0   3
## 3          tabby    3.2            1   5
## 5  tortoiseshell    3.3            1   9
## 11        calico    2.1            1   2
## 21         black    5.0            0   3
## 31         tabby    3.2            1   5
## 51 tortoiseshell    3.3            1   9

The row names have carried over from before (we got rid of row 4) and then because they had the same numbers (it was the same dataframe), they have been designated 1-1, 2-1, etc. This is unneccessarily complicated, so we can remove them and R will rename them sequentially for this new data frame.

# To remove something, we set to NULL
rownames(cats) <- NULL
cats
##            coat weight likes_string age
## 1        calico    2.1            1   2
## 2         black    5.0            0   3
## 3         tabby    3.2            1   5
## 4 tortoiseshell    3.3            1   9
## 5        calico    2.1            1   2
## 6         black    5.0            0   3
## 7         tabby    3.2            1   5
## 8 tortoiseshell    3.3            1   9

DO CHALLENGE THREE

An important point here is that you need that comma; because the data frame has two dimensions, you need to specify which rows and columns you want to grab. If you want all rows or all columns, you leave it blank - but it still needs the comma.

How to add a column and remove a column:

# Check the current columns
names(gapminder)
## [1] "country"   "year"      "pop"       "continent" "lifeExp"   "gdpPercap"
# Add a new one
gapminder$totalgdp <- gapminder$gdpPercap * gapminder$pop

# Check
names(gapminder)
## [1] "country"   "year"      "pop"       "continent" "lifeExp"   "gdpPercap"
## [7] "totalgdp"
# Remove it
gapminder$totalgdp <- NULL

# Check
names(gapminder)
## [1] "country"   "year"      "pop"       "continent" "lifeExp"   "gdpPercap"

Subsetting data: lesson 6

So you can look at the beginning, end or middle of the data to check it out. However, if there’s a particular part of the data you are interested in - for example, all the entries from a particular country only - then we need to know a bit more about subsetting data.

Selecting certain rows

In the challenge above we grabbed some data from the middle. What if we wanted certain rows?

# Grab particular rows

Subsetting data by its features

In a large dataset, we may only be interested in certain parts of it based on the information that’s in there; for example, we might only want the data for countries in Asia, or for countries with a population of over 1 million.

Here are some ways we can subset the data based on the features we want.

Removing data by features

What if the data you want to keep is much bigger than the data you want to remove? For example, if Australia’s been collecting their data wrong and we don’t care about Australia anymore.

# Remove all entries for Australia
noAust.gapminder <- gapminder[gapminder$country != "Australia",]

# Is it gone?
noAust.gapminder[noAust.gapminder$country == "Australia",]
## [1] country   year      pop       continent lifeExp   gdpPercap
## <0 rows> (or 0-length row.names)
# Remove Australia and New Zealand
noAust.noNZ.gapminder <- gapminder[!gapminder$country %in% c("Australia", "New Zealand"),]

# Are they gone?
noAust.noNZ.gapminder[noAust.noNZ.gapminder$country %in% c("Australia", "New Zealand"),]
## [1] country   year      pop       continent lifeExp   gdpPercap
## <0 rows> (or 0-length row.names)

DO CHALLENGE FIVE

Plotting: lesson 8

Okay let’s do something fun. Plotting your data is a great way to explore what’s in there, and the relationships between variables.

We start with the gapminder data. The data should be untouched (still 1704 obs of 6 variables) but if you accidentally changed it, just read it back in:

gapminder <- read.csv("data/gapminder-FiveYearData.csv")

There are a few different ways to make plots in R, and today we’ll be using the ggplot2 package because it is good at creating publication-quality graphics.

When using ggplot2, we need to think of figures in layers - let’s start with an example.

# It is a separate package, we need to load it
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp)) +
  geom_point()

The plot appears in our plots window. To explain what we’ve done here, we call the ggplot function, and now we have to give ggplot the arguments. We tell it that we want to use the gapminder data with data =. With aes (aesthetics) we tell it how the variables map to the figure - so we tell it what we want on x, and what we want on y. We didn’t have to write gapminder before these because ggplot is smart enough to look in the data for the right columns.

Then, we added another line.

Notice that the call to ggplot itself isn’t enough to draw a figure:

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp))

This tells it where things go, but not actually how to plot it. We use a new geom layer - the geom_point() function to tell ggplot that we want to plot these as a scatterplot.

DO CHALLENGE SIX

The layers don’t have to be on new lines - it will still work. But it is much easier to read if they are.

Colour

Remember that aes is aesthetics. Not only can we tell ggplot what to put on x and y, but we can tell it how to colour the points.

We can take the challenge answer for life expectancy over time, and colour the points by continent.

# You can spell colour correctly, even though documentation uses 'color'
ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = year, y = lifeExp, colour = continent)) + 
  geom_point()

Layers

This probably isn’t the best way to display change over time, so we can use a line plot instead of a scatterplot.

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = year, y = lifeExp, by = country, colour = continent)) + 
  geom_line()

Two things have changed here - we specify a geom_line layer instead of geom_point, and we’ve added the by aesthetic, which tells ggplot to draw a line for each country.

If we want to put lines and points on the same plot, we can do so - remember, we are just adding layers.

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = year, y = lifeExp, by = country, colour = continent)) + 
  geom_line() +
  geom_point()

By adding more layers, each layer is drawn on top of the previous one. So here, the points are on top of the lines. We can show this by changing some colours:

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = year, y = lifeExp, by = country)) + 
  geom_line(aes(colour = continent)) + 
  geom_point()

We have put the aesthetic mapping of colour onto the line layer, rather than on the overall plot - so the colour no longer applies to the points. With this we can see that the points are on top of the lines.

Note that aes() is used to map an aesthetic to a specific variable. If we wanted to make all of the lines blue, we wouldn’t use aes():

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = year, y = lifeExp, by = country)) + 
  geom_line(colour = "blue") + 
  geom_point()

Transformations and statistics

ggplot also makes it easy to overlay statistical models on the data. Let’s go back to our first example with colour:

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp, color=continent)) +
  geom_point()

We’ve got some strong outliers, so it’s hard to see the relationship between the points. We can do a couple of things to improve this: we can change the scale of units on the x-axis, and we can modify the transparency of the points which helps if you have heavily clustered data.

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) + 
  scale_x_log10()

The alpha function that we put within geom_point specifies the transparency of those points. The scale_x_log10 function then logs the x axis.

Remember about aesthetics and mapping - use aes() if you want to map an aesthetic to a specific variable. In this case, we wanted all of the points to be transparent, so we did it without the aes() function.

Let’s add another layer, where we fit a simple linear relationship to the plot:

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) + 
  scale_x_log10() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

This method, we are telling it which method to use to construct a linear model to fit the line.

We can make the line thicker, and let’s also give the points some colour and make them bigger:

ggplot(data = gapminder, aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5, size = 3, colour = "peachpuff3") + 
  scale_x_log10() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", size = 1.5)

DO CHALLENGE SEVEN

Multi-panel figures

So we’ve been looking at all countiries in one plot, but we can also split this over multiple panels. Let’s look at the countries that start with the letter “A” or “Z”.

Remember what we learnt about subsetting data - we only want certain countries, but this time only the “A” or “Z” at the beginning of the country name has to match.

# Let's start with a list of the first letters of all the countries
starts.with <- substr(gapminder$country, start = 1, stop = 1)

In this first part, we are actually subsetting the string - the series of characters - in the first column, country. We want to start at 1, then stop at 1 - so what we’re saying is we want the first letter.

You can look at starts.with with head() to see what it’s given you.

# Grab the rows of gapminder that begin with A or Z
az.countries <- gapminder[starts.with %in% c("A", "Z"),]

What happens here - we are specifying which rows we want. We’re actually passing it some numbers of rows behind the scenes, but to instruct R which rows they are, we use this. We want the rows of starts.with that match “A” or “Z”. Because we got the starts.with vector from gapminder, the row numbers here are the same as the ones in gapminder - so those are the rows we want. This is just one way to subset the data to the things we want.

# Now we can plot for just these countries, in facets
ggplot(data = az.countries, aes(x = year, y = lifeExp, colour = continent)) + 
  geom_line() + 
  facet_wrap("country")

This new facet_wrap layer tells R to draw a panel for each unique value of “country”.

Modifying text

Now this plot looks okay, but if we were going to publish it we’d need to clean some things up - give it proper labels and make the x-axis less cluttered. We can do this by adding some more layers.

ggplot(data = az.countries, aes(x = year, y = lifeExp, colour = continent)) + 
  geom_line() + 
  facet_wrap("country") +
  # Labs controls the labels
  labs(
    x = "Year",
    y = "Life expectancy", 
    title = "Figure 1", 
    # Title of the legend
    colour = "Continent"
  ) +
  # Draw nothing for the axis text and ticks on x
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(), axis.ticks.x = element_blank())

In RStudio, you can use the arrows to go back and forth between plots you’ve made.

Saving plots - lesson 11

You’re happy with the plot and you want to save it so you can put it in your paper.

You can:

# Save your most recent plot:
ggsave("most_recent_plot.pdf")
## Saving 7 x 5 in image

You can use Export from the plots window.

If you’re creating lots of plots (like several, one on each page) or you’ve got something automated that creates plots so you can’t click save after each one.

You can use pdf() to create a new pdf device - basically, turn on machine that makes pdfs, put things in it, then turn off machine (otherwise it’ll continue putting things in it).

pdf("Life_Exp_vs_time.pdf", width=12, height=4)
ggplot(data=gapminder, aes(x=year, y=lifeExp, colour=country)) +
  geom_line() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

# You then have to make sure to turn off the pdf device!

dev.off()
